      "content": "Modern historians generally view the UN's effectiveness in preventing major conflicts in the 21st century as mixed, acknowledging both significant diplomatic successes and persistent structural limitations. While the organization has stabilized crises through peacekeeping missions and prevented several full-scale wars by incorporating regional bodies, a consensus holds that the UN often lacks the independent coercive power needed to enforce impartiality. Ultimately, scholars agree that while the UN serves as an indispensable forum for negotiation and norm-setting, its ability to act decisively against aggression remains heavily constrained by dependency on member-state cooperation and funding.",
